Overview

This project focuses on reverse engineering Sony’s proprietary S-AIR wireless audio system and recreating its behavior using microcontrollers.

The main goal was to emulate the Sony EZW-RT10A wireless module using an STM32F103, allowing custom audio to be injected into the Sony TA-SA100WR surround amplifier.

Additionally, this repository includes:

ESP32-based transmitter emulation
ESP32-based receiver/audio conversion
Real-time I2S format conversion for external amplifiers
What This Project Does
✅ Emulates EZW-RT10A using STM32F103
✅ Reproduces Sony I2C protocol (0x40 / 0x41)
✅ Implements LINK and INT behavior
✅ Enables audio injection into Sony TA-SA100WR
✅ Emulates Sony transmitter using ESP32
✅ Converts Sony I2S → standard I2S for external boards
✅ Drives Samsung TV amplifier (TAS5749M)

System Architecture
🔹 EZW-RT10A Emulation (Audio Injection)
Hardware Used
STM32F103 (Blue Pill)
ESP32
Sony EZW-RT10A module
Sony TA-SA100WR
Sony DAV-HDX589W (for sniffing/reference)
M5Stack ES8388 audio codec
Samsung TV audio board (TAS5749M)
Logic Analyzer (PulseView)
Key Concepts
📡 I2C Reverse Engineering
Address 0x40 → control/status
Address 0x41 → DSP/coefficients

Important registers:

0x13 → status polling
0x41 → link state
0x50 → 17-byte system block
0x74 → critical trigger
LINK & INT Behavior
LINK goes HIGH only after valid sequence
INT must pulse (not toggle continuously)
Timing is critical for pairing

I2S Audio Format

Sony EZW-RT10A output:

48 kHz
32-bit stereo
BCK ≈ 3.072 MHz

External amplifier requirement:

48 kHz
16-bit or mono
BCK ≈ 1.536 MHz

 Requires real-time I2S conversion (ESP32)

Tools Used
PulseView (logic analyzer)
Python (sniff parsing → arrays)
STM32 HAL
Arduino / PlatformIO (ESP32)
Python Sniff Processing

PulseView I2C logs were converted into C arrays for firmware:

Extracted transactions
Grouped by pointer
Generated replay tables

Used for:

realistic reply emulation
faster debugging
pattern detection
Key Features
Smart I2C reply system (not static replay)
State-based LINK activation
Interrupt timing emulation
Real-time audio format conversion
Modular design (STM32 + ESP32 roles separated)
Challenges
Sony requires behavior, not just signals
Timing mismatches break pairing
I2S format mismatch prevents audio
PC10T transmitter is not fully compatible

Results
✅ Successful pairing (LINK HIGH)
✅ Stable audio transmission
✅ Custom audio injected into Sony system
✅ Sony wireless audio decoded and played externally
Future Work
Full decoding of 0x41 DSP coefficients
Smarter dynamic I2C emulation (no large arrays)
Complete transmitter firmware replacement
Reverse engineering Sony S-AIR protocol at RF level

